# Make The Arch aarch64 AUR Validation Gate Publication

Status: accepted scope for v0.74.0, re-scoped after the v0.73.0 GA run. The ARM leg ran for the first time and failed at its first step on an upstream TLS certificate fault, so the work is now a fetch fix first and the gate wiring second.

## Problem

`aur-validate-arm` in `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:442` runs the full AUR recipe validation natively on aarch64 for both pkgbases, on every GA release, and its result cannot stop a bad package from reaching the AUR.

The job is scheduled by the same condition as the x86_64 validator: a successful `workflow_run` of the Release workflow on a GA `v*` tag with no `-` in it (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:443-451`), plus an opt-in `inputs.aur_validate_arm` branch for manual dispatch. It runs `runs-on: ubuntu-24.04-arm` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:459`) over `matrix: pkgbase: [chan, chan-desktop]` with `fail-fast: false` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:455-458`). It imports and signature-verifies the Arch Linux ARM rootfs (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:470-483`) and then runs the same entry point the x86_64 job runs, `packaging/distros/arch/build-in-ci.sh` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:485-488` against `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:414-417`).

Two lines make it advisory. It carries `continue-on-error: true` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:454`), and `aur-publish` depends only on the x86_64 leg: `needs: [aur-auth, aur-validate]` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:499`). The AUR recipes declare `arch=('x86_64' 'aarch64')`, so the AUR serves aarch64 users a recipe whose native build is observed but never enforced. `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:23`, `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:57`, `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:63` and `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:65` state this arrangement as the v0.73.0 position and name v0.74.0 as the release that adds the dependency.

## First-run evidence

The v0.73.0 GA run (`publish-downstream` run id 29781883990) executed the ARM leg for the first time. Both `aur-validate-arm` cells, `chan` and `chan-desktop`, failed at the very first step, `Import the Arch Linux ARM rootfs`, with `curl: (60) SSL: no alternative certificate subject name matches target host name 'os.archlinuxarm.org'`. The certificate presented by the Arch Linux ARM download host does not list its own hostname among its subject alternative names. This is a third-party infrastructure fault on someone else's server, not a defect in chan's recipe, script, or workflow logic.

Because the failure happened at the download, everything below it on aarch64 remains unproven rather than broken. Nothing in the ARM path has been observed to fail on its merits. One certificate error is not evidence that "ARM is broken."

The rest of the same run: `aur-validate (chan)` and `aur-validate (chan-desktop)` both succeeded, the first time AUR validation has ever passed, unblocked by routing the post-install `systemd-analyze verify` through sudo (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:134`, with the sudoers rule at `packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:33-38`). Both `aur-publish` cells reported failure with `the AUR did not report <pkgbase> 0.73.0-1 after the push`, but the push itself succeeded: the job log carries git push output to `ssh://aur.archlinux.org/chan.git`, and the AUR RPC now reports `chan` 0.73.0-1 and `chan-desktop` 0.73.0-1, maintainer `fiorix`, LastModified 2026-07-20T22:21:56Z and 22:21:59Z, the moment of the push. Both pkgbases were previously unclaimed, so this run created both AUR repositories. The publication succeeded; the post-push verification poll at `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:563-584` produced a false red because it polled the RPC index before it had caught up for a brand-new pkgbase. That poll is not this item's subject and is not fixed here.

The gating decision is vindicated and is recorded here as the outcome, not a prediction. `aur-validate-arm` carried `continue-on-error: true` and stayed out of `aur-publish`'s `needs`, so a certificate misconfiguration on a third party's web server did not block chan's first ever AUR publication. Wired as a hard dependency, it would have.

## The fetch is signature-verified, not TLS-verified

The rootfs download is in the workflow, not in the container script. This corrects both the brief for this rewrite and acceptance step 4 of the previous version of this item, which placed the rootfs import inside `packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh`. It is not there; that script's ARM-specific surface begins at the keyring bootstrap. The download is `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:470-483`, verbatim:

- `base=https://os.archlinuxarm.org/os/ArchLinuxARM-aarch64-latest.tar.gz` (`:473`), fetched with `curl -fsSL --retry 3` along with its detached `.sig` (`:474-475`);
- `gpg --batch --keyserver hkps://keyserver.ubuntu.com --recv-keys 68B3537F39A313B3E574D06777193F152BDBE6A6` (`:476-477`);
- a re-read of the imported key's fingerprint through `gpg --batch --with-colons --fingerprint` and `awk`, asserted equal to the same pinned value by `test "$fingerprint" = 68B3537F39A313B3E574D06777193F152BDBE6A6` (`:478-481`), so a keyserver that answers with a different key fails the step;
- `gpg --batch --verify /tmp/archlinuxarm.tar.gz.sig /tmp/archlinuxarm.tar.gz` (`:482`) before `docker import` (`:483`).

The integrity control on this artifact is the detached signature against a pinned fingerprint. TLS on `os.archlinuxarm.org` contributes confidentiality and host authenticity for the transport, but a tampered or substituted tarball is caught by `gpg --batch --verify` regardless of which host served it. That is what makes switching to a different mirror defensible: the trust anchor is the pinned key, not the certificate, and the signature check is applied identically to whatever bytes arrive.

The same fact makes the tempting fix the wrong one. Adding `--insecure` (or `-k`) to the `curl` calls would turn the run green immediately and would remove the only transport check while leaving the impression that verification was preserved. It also silently weakens the `.sig` fetch and would accept any MITM's tarball up to the point where the signature happens to catch it. Do not disable certificate verification. Change the host, keep the check.

## Desired contract

Three things in sequence, in this order, and the third only after the second.

1. The rootfs fetch is resilient to a single upstream host being misconfigured or down. Prefer a mirror that presents a valid certificate for its own hostname, over HTTPS with verification on, fetching both the tarball and its `.sig` from the same place. Keep `gpg --batch --verify` against the pinned fingerprint `68B3537F39A313B3E574D06777193F152BDBE6A6` exactly as it is at `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:476-482`; it is the integrity control and it must run on whatever the fetch produced. A fallback list is acceptable; a bare fallback that skips the signature check is not, and neither is any relaxation of certificate verification.
2. One green `aur-validate-arm` cell for each pkgbase, from a real run, is on record.
3. Only then, in one edit and one commit: `continue-on-error: true` is removed from `aur-validate-arm` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:454`), and `aur-validate-arm` joins `aur-publish`'s `needs` alongside `aur-auth` and `aur-validate` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:499`).

A failing aarch64 build, namcap error, install, or smoke then holds back both AUR pushes, exactly as an x86_64 failure already does per `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:65`. `aur-validate-arm` still uploads no `aur-metadata-*` artifact; the x86_64 matrix remains the sole producer of the published `PKGBUILD` and `.SRCINFO` (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:419-427`).

The manual-dispatch opt-in interacts with the new dependency and must be resolved in the same edit as step 3. On `workflow_dispatch`, `aur-validate-arm` runs only when `inputs.aur_validate_arm` is true (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:444-447`), while `aur-publish` has no such condition (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:491-498`). A skipped dependency skips its dependents, so a plain `targets=aur` dispatch without the ARM switch would stop publishing. Pick one of: make `aur-publish` tolerate a skipped ARM dependency with an explicit `if` that still fails on a failed ARM result, or drop the dispatch-time opt-in so ARM always runs on an AUR dispatch. Whichever is chosen, a dispatch that skips ARM must never publish while an ARM failure silently disappears.

## Acceptance

Each check below names the deliberate mutation that must turn it red. A check that cannot be made to fail is not evidence.

1. The fetch reaches a rootfs over a certificate-valid host. Prove it by running the `Import the Arch Linux ARM rootfs` step to completion in a `workflow_dispatch` with `aur_validate_arm=true` and `publish=false` on the fix branch. Red on demand: point the primary URL at a host that does not serve the file and delete the fallback entries; the step must fail at `curl` rather than proceed.
2. The fallback is real and not decorative. Red on demand: temporarily make the first candidate unreachable and re-run; the step must still complete through `docker import` using a later candidate. If it fails, the fallback is not wired.
3. The signature check still fails closed after the fetch change. Red on demand, one at a time: flip a byte in `/tmp/archlinuxarm.tar.gz` between download and `gpg --batch --verify`, which must fail the step; and change one hex digit of the pinned fingerprint in the `test` at `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:481`, which must fail the step before any verify runs. Both mutations are reverted before the branch merges.
4. No `--insecure`, `-k`, `GIT_SSL_NO_VERIFY`, `CURL_CA_BUNDLE=/dev/null`, or equivalent appears in the diff. Red on demand: a reviewer greps the diff for those tokens; a hit rejects the change.
5. Both `aur-validate-arm` cells, `chan` and `chan-desktop`, reach a green conclusion in one run, recorded by run URL and per-cell conclusion. This exercises, for the first time, the surface listed under Unproven surface below. Only the owner can read this; it requires the authenticated run history for `fiorix/chan`.
6. After step 5, apply the two-line gate change plus the dispatch resolution, and prove it with `actionlint` over `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml` plus a reading of the resulting job graph. Red on demand for the graph claim: on a throwaway branch, inject a failing command at the top of the `Render, build, install, and smoke` step of `aur-validate-arm` and dispatch `targets=aur publish=false`; `aur-publish` must not run. Red on demand for the skip path: dispatch `targets=aur publish=false` without `aur_validate_arm`; the workflow must either run ARM anyway or refuse to publish, never publish with ARM skipped.
7. The next GA release after the change shows `aur-publish` running after four green validation cells (two architectures times two pkgbases) and both AUR repositories at the new `X.Y.Z-1`. The owner reads this from the run and from the AUR RPC; there is no local substitute.

## Unproven surface

Still unobserved on aarch64, because the run never got past the download. If any of it fails once the fetch is fixed, that failure becomes part of this item and gating follows the fix.

- The keyring bootstrap: the `archlinuxarm-keyring` branch that runs `pacman-key --init` and `pacman-key --populate archlinuxarm` (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:23-26`), reachable only from an imported ALARM rootfs.
- The rolling `pacman -Syu --needed --noconfirm base-devel curl namcap sudo` on that branch (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:26`), which upgrades the whole rootfs rather than taking the split `-Sy`/`-Su` the upstream Arch image takes (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:28-29`).
- Dependency resolution through `makepkg --cleanbuild --force --syncdeps --noconfirm` (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:96`), against `makedepends` that Arch Linux ARM must satisfy for both recipes (`packaging/distros/arch/aur/chan/PKGBUILD.in:19`, `packaging/distros/arch/aur/chan-desktop/PKGBUILD.in:30`).
- The native aarch64 Tauri build for `chan-desktop`: `npm --prefix web ci` then `cargo build --frozen --release -p chan-desktop` against the host WebKitGTK stack (`packaging/distros/arch/aur/chan-desktop/PKGBUILD.in:45`, `packaging/distros/arch/aur/chan-desktop/PKGBUILD.in:55`).
- The namcap error gate, including whether the x86_64 waiver set still fits an aarch64 package (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:70-121`).
- The install and smoke steps: `pacman -U`, `chan --version`, `cs --help`, `systemd-analyze verify` on the user unit, the packaged-upgrade refusal, and the `chan-desktop` stamp, desktop entry, and five icon sizes (`packaging/distros/arch/build-in-container.sh:125-160`). All proven on x86_64 in the v0.73.0 GA run and all unproven on aarch64.

## Boundaries

- The fetch fix and the gate change are separate commits, in that order, with a green ARM run between them. Removing `continue-on-error` before the leg can pass would block AUR publication on a fault chan does not control.
- Removing `continue-on-error` and adding the `needs` entry happen in the same edit and the same commit. The workflow must never contain a job that both gates publication and is allowed to fail, in either order of application.
- The fetch fix is confined to the `Import the Arch Linux ARM rootfs` step (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:470-483`). The gate change is confined to `.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml` plus the prose in `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:23`, `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:57`, `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:63` and `packaging/distros/arch/README.md:65` that describes the ARM leg as observed rather than gating. No recipe, `build-in-container.sh`, or `build-in-ci.sh` change belongs in this item unless a green fetch exposes a real ARM failure.
- The pinned fingerprint and the `gpg --batch --verify` call are not weakened, made conditional, or moved behind a fallback branch that can skip them.
- The false red from the post-push AUR RPC poll (`.github/workflows/publish-downstream.yml:563-584`) is out of scope here and belongs to its own item. Do not fold a poll-timing fix into this one.
- No other publication path is touched. COPR, Launchpad, and the Docker jobs are separate jobs in the same workflow and separate from the Release workflow entirely; aarch64 on COPR is already green.
- The x86_64 leg stays the sole source of published AUR metadata. Adding aarch64 as a gate must not make it a producer, or the two matrices could race to define what gets pushed.
